Wait, I'm looking at the SDEvaluator more carefully. The issue might be with how I'm handling the arrays of values. Let me check the SDEnv.cons method again - it takes a JamVal[] and returns a ConsSDEnv. So the environment is a stack of value arrays. When I do environment.cons(vals), I'm adding the new array of values to the environment, which seems correct.

Actually, looking at the original SymEvaluator code for forLetRec, I see a pattern where it uses Binding objects and a special setBinding method. But for SDEvaluator, I'm directly modifying the array. Let me check if this is correct by looking at the SDClosure class again.

Looking at SDClosure:
```java
public JamVal apply(JamVal[] args) {
    SDEnv newEnv = eval.env();
    int n = smap.arity();
    if (n != args.length) throw new EvalException("closure " + this + " applied to " + 
       args.length + " arguments instead of " + n + " arguments");
      newEnv = newEnv.cons(args);
    return smap.body().accept((SDASTVisitor<JamVal>) eval.newEvalVisitor(newEnv));
  }
```

When a closure is applied, it adds the arguments to the environment via `newEnv.cons(args)`, then creates a new evaluator with the updated environment and evaluates the body. In my forSLet implementation, I'm following the same pattern: evaluating all right-hand sides to get values, adding them to the environment with `env.cons(vals)`, then evaluating the body with a new visitor using that environment.

For forSLetRec, I'm creating an array of null values, building the environment with `env.cons(vals)`, then evaluating each right-hand side with the new evaluator so they can reference each other. The key insight is that modifying the array in place after environment creation should work because the environment holds a reference to that same array. I need to verify this matches how ConsSDEnv.lookup retrieves values from the array. v
4. Use that evaluator to evaluate the rhss

The evaluator holds a reference to newEnv, which contains vals. When I populate vals[i] with each evaluated rhs, those mutations are immediately visible to any lookups through newEnv. This means closures created during evaluation will see the correct bound values when they're later invoked. Let me trace through a recursive example like `letrec f := map x to f(x); in f(5)` to verify the approach works—when f's body is evaluated, it can reference f itself through the environment lookup since vals will already contain the closure by that point. The newEvalVisitor method returns a fresh SDEvaluator initialized with newEnv, so when I evaluate each right-hand side, any closures created will capture this evaluator and its environment. This means the closures will have access to the vals array that's being populated. However, I need to verify that newEvalVisitor is actually a method that constructs a new evaluator rather than returning a cached instance. The return type of `newEvalVisitor(SDEnv env)` is `SDASTVisitor<JamVal>`, which matches what I'm returning from my implementation. In the `SDClosure.apply` method, I cast the result of `eval.newEvalVisitor(newEnv)` to `SDASTVisitor<JamVal>` when passing it to the body's accept method, which should work correctly since `eval` is an `SDEvaluator`. The implementation appears sound, so I should test it to identify any runtime issues, though the main blocker seems to be the test runner's caching behavior.

